DEFAULT_BIOS = {
    "antelope": "Antelopes are swift, hoofed herbivores found mainly in Africa and parts of Asia. They are known for their speed, agility, and alertness, which help them escape predators in open grasslands and savannas. Many species live in herds and rely on keen senses and coordinated movement for protection.",
    "badger": "Badgers are sturdy, burrowing mammals with strong claws and powerful bodies built for digging. They are usually nocturnal and feed on insects, small animals, roots, and fruits. Badgers are known for being tough, determined, and highly adaptable to forests, grasslands, and farmland.",
    "bat": "Bats are the only mammals capable of sustained true flight. Many species use echolocation, sending out sound waves and listening to the echoes to navigate and hunt in darkness. Bats play important ecological roles by eating insects, pollinating flowers, and dispersing seeds in many ecosystems.",
    "bear": "Bears are large, powerful mammals found in forests, mountains, tundra, and Arctic regions. They have strong limbs, excellent senses of smell, and varied diets that may include fish, berries, roots, insects, and meat. Although they can appear slow, bears are surprisingly fast and highly intelligent.",
    "bee": "Bees are vital pollinating insects that help flowering plants reproduce and support global agriculture. Many bees live in colonies with specialized roles, including workers, drones, and a queen. Their work is essential for biodiversity, crop production, and the health of many ecosystems.",
    "beetle": "Beetles are one of the most diverse groups of animals on Earth, with thousands of species adapted to nearly every habitat. They are characterized by hard wing covers called elytra that protect their flying wings. Beetles play many ecological roles, including decomposition, pollination, and pest control.",
    "bison": "Bison are massive grazing mammals known for their strong shoulders, thick fur, and impressive endurance. They once roamed North American grasslands in huge herds and remain a symbol of strength and resilience. Bison are social animals that feed mainly on grasses and can run surprisingly fast.",
    "boar": "Boars are wild relatives of domestic pigs and are known for their toughness, intelligence, and adaptability. They have strong snouts for rooting in the soil and tusks that can be used for defense. Boars eat roots, fruits, insects, and small animals, making them opportunistic omnivores.",
    "butterfly": "Butterflies are delicate insects famous for their colorful wings and complete metamorphosis from caterpillar to adult. They feed mainly on nectar and help pollinate flowers as they move between plants. Their patterns, flight, and life cycle make them some of the most recognized insects in nature.",
    "camel": "Camels are desert-adapted mammals built for survival in hot, dry environments. They can conserve water efficiently, tolerate extreme temperatures, and travel long distances across harsh terrain. Their humps store fat, which provides energy when food is scarce, and their wide feet help them walk on sand.",
    "capybara": "Capybaras are the largest rodents in the world and are native to South America. They are highly social animals that often live near rivers, lakes, and wetlands, where they swim well and use water for safety. Capybaras are calm herbivores that feed on grasses and aquatic plants.",
    "cat": "Cats are agile, observant mammals known for balance, stealth, and quick reflexes. Domestic cats are popular pets, while wild cats include many highly skilled hunters. They use sharp senses, retractable claws, and flexible bodies to stalk prey, climb, and move quietly through different environments.",
    "caterpillar": "Caterpillars are the larval stage of butterflies and moths. Their main role is to eat and grow, often consuming large amounts of leaves before transforming through metamorphosis. Although they may seem simple, caterpillars display a wide variety of colors, hairs, patterns, and defensive adaptations.",
    "chimpanzee": "Chimpanzees are highly intelligent primates closely related to humans. They live in complex social groups, communicate with sounds and gestures, and are known to use tools for feeding and problem-solving. Chimpanzees inhabit forests and woodlands in Africa and play an important role in scientific studies of behavior and cognition.",
    "cockroach": "Cockroaches are hardy insects that have existed for millions of years and can survive in a wide range of conditions. They are scavengers that feed on decaying matter, scraps, and many organic materials. Their resilience, speed, and adaptability have made them among the most well-known insects in the world.",
    "cow": "Cows are domesticated herbivorous mammals raised worldwide for milk, meat, and agricultural work. They are ruminants, meaning they digest plant material through a specialized stomach system. Cows are social animals that often live in herds and have played a major role in human civilization and farming.",
    "coyote": "Coyotes are intelligent, adaptable canids found across North and Central America. They can live in deserts, forests, grasslands, and even urban environments. Coyotes are skilled hunters and scavengers, feeding on rodents, rabbits, fruits, and carrion, and they are known for their distinct vocalizations.",
    "crab": "Crabs are crustaceans with hard exoskeletons, strong pincers, and sideways walking behavior. They inhabit oceans, shorelines, rivers, and some land environments depending on the species. Crabs are omnivores or scavengers and play important roles in food webs and coastal ecosystems.",
    "crocodile": "Crocodiles are large semi-aquatic reptiles with powerful jaws, armored skin, and excellent ambush hunting abilities. They live in rivers, swamps, estuaries, and wetlands in tropical and subtropical regions. Crocodiles can remain still for long periods before launching sudden, powerful attacks on prey.",
    "crow": "Crows are highly intelligent birds known for problem-solving, memory, and social learning. They can recognize human faces, use tools, and adapt to city life as well as wild habitats. Their black feathers, loud calls, and clever behavior have made them one of the most studied bird groups.",
    "deer": "Deer are graceful herbivorous mammals found in forests, grasslands, and mountains around the world. Many species are known for their alert behavior, quick running, and, in males, seasonal antler growth. Deer feed on leaves, shoots, grasses, and fruits and are important prey animals in many ecosystems.",
    "dog": "Dogs are domesticated mammals valued for companionship, intelligence, and trainability. Descended from wolves, they have been bred into many forms for work, protection, hunting, and friendship. Dogs are highly social animals that can form strong bonds with humans and respond well to communication and training.",
    "dolphin": "Dolphins are intelligent marine mammals known for social behavior, communication, and acrobatic swimming. They use echolocation to navigate and locate prey in the water. Dolphins often live in pods and are admired for their curiosity, cooperation, and strong learning ability.",
    "donkey": "Donkeys are sturdy domesticated animals related to horses, known for endurance, intelligence, and sure-footed movement. They have been used for transport and farm work for thousands of years, especially in dry and mountainous regions. Donkeys are social animals with loud, distinctive brays.",
    "dragonfly": "Dragonflies are fast-flying insects with large eyes, long bodies, and two pairs of powerful transparent wings. They are skilled aerial hunters that feed on mosquitoes and other small insects. Their aquatic young, called nymphs, live in water before emerging as agile flying adults.",
    "duck": "Ducks are waterfowl with broad bills, webbed feet, and waterproof feathers. They live in ponds, lakes, marshes, rivers, and coastal areas, where they feed on plants, insects, and small aquatic animals. Ducks are excellent swimmers and many species migrate seasonally over long distances.",
    "eagle": "Eagles are large birds of prey known for powerful talons, hooked beaks, and exceptional eyesight. They hunt fish, mammals, reptiles, and birds, often soaring high to scan for movement below. Eagles are symbols of strength and freedom in many cultures due to their size and majestic flight.",
    "elephant": "Elephants are the largest land animals on Earth and are famous for their trunks, tusks, and strong family bonds. They are highly intelligent, social, and capable of memory, problem-solving, and emotional behavior. Elephants shape their environments by uprooting vegetation and creating paths and water access points.",
    "flamingo": "Flamingos are striking wading birds recognized by their long legs, curved necks, and pink feathers. Their color comes from pigments in the food they eat, such as algae and small crustaceans. Flamingos often gather in large colonies and feed by filtering food from shallow water.",
    "fly": "Flies are a large group of insects with one pair of wings and highly varied lifestyles. Some species help decompose organic matter, while others pollinate plants or act as pests. Their fast movement, short life cycles, and adaptability allow them to thrive in many habitats worldwide.",
    "fox": "Foxes are clever, adaptable members of the dog family found in forests, grasslands, deserts, and urban areas. They have sharp hearing, keen senses, and agile bodies suited for hunting small prey. Foxes are often solitary and are known for intelligence, caution, and resourcefulness.",
    "frog": "Frogs are amphibians with moist skin, strong jumping legs, and life cycles that usually include both aquatic and land stages. They begin life as tadpoles and later transform into adults through metamorphosis. Frogs are important indicators of environmental health because they are sensitive to habitat changes and pollution.",
    "giraffe": "Giraffes are the tallest land animals, known for their extremely long necks and legs. They use their height to browse leaves high in trees, especially acacias in African savannas. Giraffes have unique coat patterns, strong kicks for defense, and specialized blood circulation adapted to their size.",
    "goat": "Goats are hardy domesticated herbivores known for agility, curiosity, and adaptability. They can live in mountains, grasslands, and dry regions, feeding on a wide range of vegetation. Goats have long been important to humans for milk, meat, fiber, and their ability to thrive in difficult environments.",
    "goldfish": "Goldfish are freshwater fish commonly kept as pets and known for their bright colors and calm swimming behavior. They are domesticated varieties of carp and can live much longer than many people expect when cared for properly. Goldfish use gills to breathe and thrive in clean, well-maintained aquatic habitats.",
    "goose": "Geese are large water birds known for strong family bonds, loud calls, and seasonal migration. They feed mainly on grasses, aquatic plants, and grains, often traveling in groups. Their V-shaped flight formations help conserve energy during long journeys.",
    "gorilla": "Gorillas are the largest living primates and are known for strength, intelligence, and complex social groups. They live in African forests and usually feed on leaves, stems, fruit, and other plant material. Gorillas are generally gentle animals led by dominant males called silverbacks.",
    "grasshopper": "Grasshoppers are jumping insects with powerful hind legs and strong chewing mouthparts. They feed mainly on grasses and leaves and can be found in fields, meadows, and open habitats. Their ability to leap quickly helps them escape predators, and some species produce sounds by rubbing body parts together.",
    "hamster": "Hamsters are small rodents known for cheek pouches used to store food and carry nesting material. They are often nocturnal and spend much of their time digging, hiding, and foraging. Hamsters are popular pets because of their small size, active behavior, and manageable care needs.",
    "hare": "Hares are fast-running mammals related to rabbits but generally larger, with longer ears and longer hind legs. Unlike many rabbits, hares often live above ground and rely on speed to escape predators. They are herbivores that feed on grasses, shoots, and bark.",
    "hedgehog": "Hedgehogs are small mammals covered in spines that serve as protection against predators. When threatened, they can roll into a tight ball to shield their face and body. Hedgehogs usually feed on insects and other small invertebrates and are mostly active at night.",
    "hippopotamus": "Hippopotamuses are massive semi-aquatic mammals that spend much of the day in rivers and lakes to stay cool. Despite their bulky appearance, they can move quickly on land and are considered one of Africa’s most dangerous large animals. Hippos feed mostly on grasses and play a major role in freshwater ecosystems.",
    "hornbill": "Hornbills are distinctive birds with large curved bills, often topped by a casque on the upper beak. They are found in Africa and Asia and feed on fruits, insects, and small animals. Many hornbill species are known for unusual nesting behavior in which the female seals herself inside a tree cavity while raising young.",
    "horse": "Horses are powerful herbivorous mammals that have worked alongside humans for thousands of years in transport, farming, sport, and companionship. They are built for speed and endurance, with strong legs and social herd behavior. Horses communicate through body language, vocalizations, and subtle movement.",
    "hummingbird": "Hummingbirds are tiny birds famous for rapid wingbeats and the ability to hover in place. They feed mainly on nectar, using long bills and tongues to reach deep into flowers, while also helping pollinate plants. Their speed, bright colors, and precise flight make them some of the most remarkable birds.",
    "hyena": "Hyenas are intelligent carnivorous mammals known for strong jaws, endurance, and complex social groups. Although often thought of mainly as scavengers, many hyenas are highly skilled hunters. They play an important role in ecosystems by consuming carrion and controlling prey populations.",
    "jellyfish": "Jellyfish are soft-bodied marine animals with umbrella-shaped bodies and trailing tentacles. Many species use stinging cells to capture prey and defend themselves. Although they lack bones and a true brain, jellyfish have survived for millions of years and are found in oceans around the world.",
    "kangaroo": "Kangaroos are iconic marsupials from Australia known for powerful hind legs, long tails, and hopping movement. Females carry their young, called joeys, in a pouch while they continue to develop. Kangaroos are herbivores that live in grasslands and open habitats and often move in groups.",
    "koala": "Koalas are tree-dwelling marsupials native to Australia and are known for their thick fur, round ears, and sleepy appearance. They feed mainly on eucalyptus leaves, which provide limited energy, so koalas spend much of their time resting. They are specialized animals with strong claws for climbing.",
    "ladybugs": "Ladybugs, also called ladybird beetles, are small rounded insects often recognized by bright colors and spotted wing covers. Many species are beneficial because they eat aphids and other plant pests. Their color patterns can warn predators that they may taste unpleasant or release defensive chemicals.",
    "leopard": "Leopards are powerful, adaptable big cats known for spotted coats, stealth, and climbing ability. They live in forests, savannas, and mountains across parts of Africa and Asia. Leopards are solitary hunters that often drag prey into trees to protect it from scavengers.",
    "lion": "Lions are large social cats that live mainly in African grasslands, with a small population in India. Unlike most big cats, lions often live in prides made up of related females, cubs, and a few males. They are powerful predators and major symbols of strength, courage, and dominance.",
    "lizard": "Lizards are reptiles with scaly skin, clawed feet, and a wide range of sizes, colors, and lifestyles. Some live in deserts, others in forests, rocks, or even trees, and many can detach their tails to escape predators. Lizards feed on insects, plants, or small animals depending on the species.",
    "lobster": "Lobsters are marine crustaceans with hard shells, strong claws, and long antennae. They live on the ocean floor and feed on fish, mollusks, and plant material. Lobsters grow by molting, shedding their exoskeleton as they become larger over time.",
    "mandrill": "Mandrills are large colorful primates native to the rainforests of central Africa. Males are especially known for vivid blue and red facial features and strong social presence. Mandrills live in groups and feed on fruits, seeds, insects, and small animals.",
    "mantis": "Mantises are predatory insects known for their folded forelegs, triangular heads, and patient ambush hunting style. They remain motionless for long periods before striking prey with great speed. Their body shape and behavior often provide excellent camouflage among leaves and branches.",
    "mosquito": "Mosquitoes are small flying insects known for feeding on blood in many species, although both adults and larvae are part of broader aquatic and terrestrial food webs. Females of some species require blood to produce eggs, while mosquitoes also feed on plant sugars. They are important in public health because some species can transmit diseases.",
    "moth": "Moths are insects related to butterflies and are often active at night. They display tremendous diversity in size, color, and wing shape, with some species acting as pollinators and others as agricultural pests. Like butterflies, moths undergo complete metamorphosis from caterpillar to adult.",
    "mouse": "Mice are small rodents with sharp senses, quick movement, and high reproductive rates. They are found in many habitats and often feed on seeds, grains, fruits, and scraps. Mice play important roles in ecosystems as prey animals and are also widely used in scientific research.",
    "octopus": "Octopuses are highly intelligent marine animals with eight flexible arms, excellent camouflage, and problem-solving ability. They can squeeze through tiny spaces, change color and texture, and manipulate objects with surprising precision. Octopuses are solitary hunters that feed on crabs, mollusks, and fish.",
    "orangutan": "Orangutans are great apes native to the rainforests of Borneo and Sumatra. They are highly intelligent, mostly solitary, and spend much of their time in trees, where they build nests for resting. Orangutans feed largely on fruit and are important seed dispersers in tropical forests.",
    "otter": "Otters are playful, streamlined mammals adapted for life in rivers, lakes, and coastal waters. They have dense fur, webbed feet, and strong swimming ability that help them catch fish and other aquatic prey. Many otter species use tools, show social behavior, and are considered indicators of healthy waterways.",
    "owl": "Owls are nocturnal birds of prey known for forward-facing eyes, silent flight, and exceptional hearing. They hunt rodents, insects, and other small animals, often under the cover of darkness. Their rotating heads and sharp talons make them highly effective nighttime predators.",
    "panda": "Pandas are bear-like mammals best known for their distinctive black-and-white fur and strong association with bamboo forests in China. Although they belong to the order Carnivora, giant pandas feed mainly on bamboo and spend much of their day eating. Pandas are symbols of conservation and wildlife protection worldwide.",
    "pangolin": "Pangolins are unusual mammals covered in protective keratin scales. They feed mostly on ants and termites, using strong claws to break open nests and long sticky tongues to capture insects. When threatened, pangolins curl into a ball, relying on their scales for defense.",
    "parrot": "Parrots are colorful, intelligent birds with curved beaks and strong feet adapted for climbing and grasping food. Many species are capable of learning sounds and mimicking human speech. Parrots often live in tropical forests and feed on seeds, fruits, nuts, and blossoms.",
    "peacock": "The peacock, or male peafowl, is famous for its brilliant iridescent tail feathers displayed during courtship. These birds are ground-feeding omnivores that eat seeds, insects, and small creatures. Their dramatic plumage and display behavior make them some of the most recognizable birds in the world.",
    "pelecaniformes": "Pelecaniformes is a bird group that includes pelicans and several related waterbirds. Members of this group are often associated with wetlands, lakes, coastlines, and shallow waters where they catch fish and other aquatic prey. They are recognized for their aquatic habits, long bills, and adaptations for feeding in water.",
    "penguin": "Penguins are flightless seabirds adapted for life in the water, using their wings as flippers for swimming. They have dense waterproof feathers and strong social behavior, often nesting in colonies. Penguins feed on fish, squid, and krill and are found mainly in the Southern Hemisphere.",
    "pig": "Pigs are intelligent omnivorous mammals known for strong snouts, social behavior, and excellent sense of smell. Domestic pigs are raised worldwide, while wild relatives thrive in forests and grasslands. Pigs are curious, adaptable animals that can learn quickly and solve simple problems.",
    "pigeon": "Pigeons are hardy birds found in cities, farms, cliffs, and forests across the world. They are known for navigation ability, flocking behavior, and close historical relationships with humans as messengers and domestic birds. Pigeons feed mainly on seeds, grains, and scraps.",
    "platypus": "The platypus is one of the most unusual mammals on Earth, combining traits that seem to belong to several animal groups. Native to Australia, it lays eggs, has a duck-like bill, webbed feet, and dense waterproof fur. Platypuses hunt aquatic invertebrates using electroreception in murky water.",
    "porcupine": "Porcupines are rodents covered with sharp quills that protect them from predators. They feed mainly on bark, leaves, stems, and other plant material, often climbing trees or moving slowly along the ground. Their defensive quills make them one of the most recognizable mammals.",
    "possum": "Possums are marsupials known for adaptability, climbing ability, and, in some species, a prehensile tail. They often feed on fruit, insects, leaves, eggs, and small animals. Some possums are famous for defensive behavior that resembles 'playing dead' when threatened.",
    "pufferfish": "Pufferfish are unusual fish known for the ability to inflate their bodies when threatened, making them harder for predators to swallow. Many species also contain powerful toxins that provide additional defense. They inhabit marine and some freshwater environments and often feed on invertebrates and algae.",
    "raccoon": "Raccoons are intelligent, dexterous mammals recognized by their black facial mask and ringed tails. They are highly adaptable and often thrive in forests, wetlands, suburbs, and cities. Raccoons use sensitive front paws to explore food and objects, feeding on fruits, insects, eggs, and small animals.",
    "reindeer": "Reindeer, also known as caribou in North America, are cold-adapted deer that live in Arctic and sub-Arctic regions. They are famous for seasonal migrations, thick insulating coats, and broad hooves that help them move over snow and soft ground. Reindeer feed on lichens, grasses, and shrubs.",
    "rhinoceros": "Rhinoceroses are large herbivorous mammals with thick skin and one or two horns made of keratin. They live in parts of Africa and Asia and feed on grasses, leaves, and shrubs depending on the species. Rhinos are powerful animals that play important ecological roles but face major conservation threats.",
    "sandpiper": "Sandpipers are shorebirds that typically have slender bills and long legs suited for probing mud, sand, and shallow water for food. They feed on worms, crustaceans, and small invertebrates along coasts and wetlands. Many sandpiper species are migratory and travel impressive distances between breeding and wintering grounds.",
    "scallop": "Scallops are marine shellfish belonging to the mollusk group. Unlike many shellfish, some scallops can swim by rapidly opening and closing their shells to move through water. They live on or near the seafloor and feed by filtering tiny food particles from the water.",
    "scorpion": "Scorpions are arachnids with pincers, segmented tails, and venomous stingers used for hunting and defense. They are mostly nocturnal and often live in deserts, rocky habitats, forests, and grasslands. Scorpions feed on insects and other small animals and have survived for hundreds of millions of years.",
    "seahorse": "Seahorses are small marine fish with upright posture, curled tails, and horse-like head shapes. They swim slowly and often anchor themselves to plants or coral using their tails. Seahorses are famous for unique reproduction in which the male carries the developing young in a brood pouch.",
    "seal": "Seals are marine mammals adapted to life in cold and temperate oceans. They have streamlined bodies, flippers for swimming, and thick layers of fat that help insulate them in chilly waters. Seals feed on fish, squid, and crustaceans and often rest on ice, rocks, or beaches.",
    "shark": "Sharks are cartilaginous fish known for streamlined bodies, sharp teeth, and highly developed senses. They occupy many marine habitats, from coral reefs to deep oceans, and serve as important predators in aquatic food webs. Different shark species vary widely in size, diet, and behavior.",
    "sheep": "Sheep are domesticated grazing mammals valued for wool, meat, and milk. They are social herd animals that feed mainly on grasses and are well suited to life on farms and grasslands. Their thick coats and group behavior have made them important to human societies for thousands of years.",
    "snake": "Snakes are legless reptiles with flexible bodies, scales, and specialized methods of movement. Depending on the species, they may constrict prey, use venom, or swallow animals whole after capturing them. Snakes inhabit deserts, forests, wetlands, and oceans, making them one of the most diverse reptile groups.",
    "sparrow": "Sparrows are small active birds commonly found in grasslands, farms, towns, and cities. They feed on seeds, grains, and insects and are known for quick movement and social flocking behavior. Their adaptability has allowed many sparrow species to live successfully alongside humans.",
    "spider": "Spiders are arachnids with eight legs and the ability, in many species, to produce silk for webs, egg sacs, and movement. They are important predators of insects and help control pest populations in natural and human environments. Spider species vary greatly in size, hunting style, and habitat.",
    "squid": "Squid are fast-swimming marine animals related to octopuses and cuttlefish. They have elongated bodies, tentacles, excellent vision, and the ability to jet through water quickly. Squid are important predators and prey in ocean ecosystems and many species can change color for communication or camouflage.",
    "squirrel": "Squirrels are agile rodents known for bushy tails, sharp claws, and climbing ability. Many species live in trees, where they gather nuts, seeds, fruits, and fungi, while others live on the ground. Squirrels are famous for caching food and their quick, energetic movement.",
    "starfish": "Starfish, more accurately called sea stars, are marine animals with radial symmetry and usually five arms. They move using tiny tube feet and can often regenerate lost limbs. Sea stars feed on shellfish and other small marine organisms and are common in coastal and seabed habitats.",
    "swan": "Swans are large elegant water birds with long necks and strong family bonds. They glide across lakes, rivers, and wetlands, feeding on aquatic plants and small invertebrates. Swans are often associated with beauty and grace because of their appearance and smooth movement on water.",
    "tiger": "Tigers are the largest wild cats and are known for powerful bodies, striped coats, and solitary hunting behavior. They live in forests, grasslands, and wetlands across parts of Asia, stalking prey with stealth and strength. Tigers are iconic predators and important symbols of biodiversity conservation.",
    "turkey": "Turkeys are large ground-dwelling birds native to North America. Wild turkeys are strong runners and short-distance fliers, feeding on seeds, insects, fruits, and small animals. They are known for social behavior, keen eyesight, and distinctive courtship displays.",
    "turtle": "Turtles are reptiles recognized by their protective shells, which are part of their skeleton. Different species live in oceans, rivers, lakes, or on land, feeding on plants, invertebrates, or small animals. Turtles are long-lived and many species migrate or return to specific nesting areas.",
    "walrus": "Walruses are large Arctic marine mammals known for long tusks, whiskered snouts, and thick layers of blubber. They use their tusks for social display, defense, and hauling themselves onto ice. Walruses feed mainly on clams and other bottom-dwelling animals in cold northern seas.",
    "whale": "Whales are large marine mammals that include both baleen whales and toothed whales. They breathe air, nurse their young, and are adapted for life in oceans through streamlined bodies and powerful tails. Many whale species are known for long migrations, communication, and important ecological roles in marine systems.",
    "wombat": "Wombats are sturdy burrowing marsupials native to Australia. They have strong claws, powerful legs, and compact bodies adapted for digging tunnels and foraging on grasses and roots. Wombats are mostly nocturnal and are known for their calm but determined nature.",
    "woodpecker": "Woodpeckers are birds specialized for climbing tree trunks and pecking into wood in search of insects or nesting space. They have strong neck muscles, chisel-like beaks, and shock-absorbing skull adaptations. Their drumming sounds are used for communication and territory marking.",
    "zebra": "Zebras are African hoofed mammals recognized by their bold black-and-white stripes, each with a unique pattern. They live in herds and rely on speed, alertness, and group behavior to avoid predators. Zebras graze on grasses and are closely related to horses and donkeys.",
}
